I always enjoyed this saga because of its choreography, that was thought and, if not realistic, at least plausible and the theme, with the assassins guilds that had rules and whatnot.In this movie, that has all been thrown away in favor of more bangbangs:
1. Bulletproof suits, choreography is not necessary anymore as you can just shoot at each other and it simply bounce;
2. Immortal characters: let's forget for a minute about the (useless) shooting and let's focus on John Wick. How many high speed impacts does he sustain? In the (laughable) roundabout scene alone he gets hit by a number of cars, he rolls 250+ steps and he falls from the third floor of a building and the only consequence is hurtng his finger?3. The assassins: a blind samurai, a black cowboy and a german in a fat foam suit. Is this the beginning of a joke?4. The "special forces": has he really killed all the proper assassins in the previous movie? Because the special forces looks like kids with a gun.The whole movie was ridiculous and it killed the franchise.

Lets talk positives first;
If you like action, and liked the first three movies especially for the action; you're in for a hell of a ride with this one. The action is superb, with shots and angles and stunts you have never seen before.That's about it, yeaahLets talk negatives then;
Keanu reeves, as sympathetic as he might be in person, deserves a golden raspberry for this performance. His dialogue fits onto less than one sheet of paper (in a 3 hour movie!!) from which half is just an overly dramatic >>yeaah<< or >>maybe<< which the other guests found to be funny while I found it odd, even ridiculous as it went on. His performance completely pulled me out of the immersion. Very unsatisfying.The protagonist John Wick does literally nothing in this movie that regains our sympathy for him.They just throw him in there and say >>that's the protagonist, go root for him<<, but I just had a hard time swallowing that pill which lead to me not having fun on his journey to get away from the tableOn a different note,
I already mentioned the inflated runtime of 170 minutes. This is at least 40 minutes too long! They could have completely get rid of Shamier Anderson's character and nothing would have changed about the outcome of the movie, which wasn't particularly bad but also not shocking, as it was rather poorly foreshadowed.All in all, the action in this is world class, perhaps the best action in a movie ever, but as soon as the action was over, the fun was over as well.

John Wick: Chapter 4 is a stunning, action-packed film that delivers on all fronts. The set pieces are fantastic and brilliant, the plot is unpredictable, the cinematography is great, and it is a rare feat that every John Wick sequel is better than its predecessor.The film picks up right where the third film left off, with John Wick on the run from the High Table. He travels to Japan, France, and Berlin, seeking revenge on those who have wronged him.The set pieces in John Wick: Chapter 4 are simply breathtaking. There are multiple extended action sequences that will leave you breathless. The film's director, Chad Stahelski, has a gift for staging and choreographing action scenes, and he pulls out all the stops in this film.The plot of John Wick: Chapter 4 is also very unpredictable. The film is full of twists and turns, and you never know what's going to happen next. This makes the film very exciting to watch.The cinematography in John Wick: Chapter 4 is also very good. The film is beautifully shot, and the action sequences are framed in a way that makes them even more exciting.Overall, John Wick: Chapter 4 is an excellent film. It is a must-see for fans of action movies and Keanu Reeves. If you're looking for a film that will leave you breathless, then this is the film for you.Here are some of the pros and cons of the movie:Pros:
Fantastic and brilliant set pieces;
Unpredictable plot;
Great cinematography;
Better than its predecessor.Cons:
Some scenes may be too violent for some viewers;
The plot can be a bit convoluted at times;
The film is quite long.
